metadata.name: Memory Module #127
metadata.description:
Day by day, memories accumulate and shape our dreams, subconscious, ideals, and ultimately, the innermost self. 

This artwork is created by repeatedly drawing squares that are identical in size, with each one representing a memory. As new memories form, the older ones become obscured, fuzzy, or joined with others to form belief structures and intuitions. I hope that this work will remind you of someone, someplace, a song or a melody that‚Äôs important to you. 

Keyboard controls:
[S] Save the current view in live mode.
[1] to [8] Change resolution, 1.5K to 12K.
[G] Toggle paper texture.

URL params:
aspect: custom aspect ratio (?aspect=3).
res: custom resolution multiplier (?res=4).

Made with fractal math and p5js, Memory Module is the first in a 5-part generative art series about introspection. You can read more about the series here: https://elsifthen.github.io/

Created by elsif, 2022.07.

metadata.name: Kinetograms #167
metadata.description:
Each Kinetogram traces the movement of a number of simple shapes constrained within a single cell or a grid of cells. Forces are applied to the shapes in the form of attraction, gravity or shaking.

Some Kinetograms are partially or completely reflected, vertically or horizontally, some with chromatic replacement.

The aspect ratio is 3:4. The palettes are predominantly based on found textile patterns.

Press 's' to save a png image. Press 'e' to redraw and export a 4K png image. Note that drawing and physical simulation takes some time.

For interactive use, press 't' to tilt the board and 'c' to clear the board.

Written in p5.js with 2D physical simulation using Matter.js. Developed in and optimized for Chrome.

metadata.name: Punktwelt #478
metadata.description:
Continuing on the theme of color perception in Farbteiler, Punktwelt is an exploration of color interaction, projection and perceived depth, and the aesthetics of simple Boolean operations on form.

Each shape is the result of a single block, a rectangular cuboid, subjected to a series of Boolean subtractions with other blocks, and rendered in parallel projection, oblique or axonometric, in the abstract landscape of the Punktwelt.

Some have horizons, some have banded or striped backgrounds. The unnatural drawing order and chromatic differences of the individual faces sometimes yields illusory or paradoxical visual geometries.

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a png. Press ‚Äô4‚Äô to export a high resolution png. Press ‚Äô8‚Äô to export a very high resolution png. Press ‚Äôe‚Äô to export an SVG file (may take some time and produce large files).

Aspect ratio variations are 4:5, 5:4, 2:3, 3:2 and 1:1.

Built in Javascript with p5.js, p5.svg and csg.js.

metadata.name: Elswhere #190
metadata.description:
Perlin noise walks into a Julia set and finds itself Elswhere. X is real, Y is imaginary, or is it the other way around? 

Elswhere is a unique generative art series in which noise and fractal math are combined to create whimsical shapes and motifs, with an infinite number of variations. Made with p5js.

For each pixel, the noise values corresponding to the X and Y coordinates are computed and then used as the real and imaginary components for initializing a Julia set recursion. The pixel is colored based on the number of steps it takes for the recursion to reach its base case.

Keyboard controls:
[S] Save the current view.
[2] Render 2000x3000px image.
[4] Render 4000x6000px image.
[6] Render 6000x9000px image.

Created by Elsif, 2022.05

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #160
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: cliques #70
metadata.description:
clique is defined as:

- /klƒìk,klik/ (n.) a small group of people, with shared interests or other features in common, who spend time together and do not readily allow others to join them.

cliques can offer safety. (something about numbers.)

cliques can offer a place to be. (for better or worse.)

sometimes cliques have sub-cliques. (the intersections can get a bit complicated.)

sometimes a member of a clique may still feel outside of it. (power dynamics can ruin things.)

occasionally clique dynamics are balanced and the connections between the members pull towards the center. (we can consider that non-toxic.)

often, though, the connections are pulled in various directions and the connection between two members are swayed (or pulled towards) other members. (we can consider that toxic.)

[4 color palettes: monochrome, neon, vibrant rebellion, glacier]

[tap ‚Äús‚Äù to save image]
[tip: zoom out to 25% first to save a higher res image]

[cc0] [p5js] [xoxo] [twitter: @heyjeres]

metadata.name: vapour trails #9
metadata.description:
‚Äúfirst you look so strong, then you fade away
the sun will blind my eyes, i‚Äôll love you anyway
thirsty for your smile, i watch you for a while
you are a vapour trail in a deep blue sky‚Äù

‚Äî Andy Bell (Ride) (1991)

this collection tries to capture that feeling of lying in the grass
in a park
staring at the sky
fantasizing about your love (if they even exist)
playing out different paths
while smoke from your cigarette (jazz or otherwise)
trails between you and the faraway of everything
feeling grateful to not have to be anywhere
but here (now)

with luck
they lay next to you
and silently you appreciate each tick of the clock
wasted together
until life again gets in the way
and pulls you back
into the fray

[ live view commands ]
[ M : toggle matte ]
[ S : save current size ]
[ 1 : save 2000x3000 png ]
[ 2 : save 4000x6000 png ]
[ 3 : save 6000x9000* png ]
[ 4 : save 8000x12000* png ]
[ 5 : save 10000x15000* png ]

* higher resolutions can take a while to render.

twitter: @heyjeres

xoxo

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #164
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to ‚Äúlush, green‚Äù and Brut means ‚Äúdry, raw, or unrefined.‚Äù

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth‚Ä¶ but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-BorgstroÃàm, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
‚ÄòS‚Äô : save as png (2376‚Ää√ó‚Ää3360)
‚ÄôV‚Äô : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‚Äòg=n‚Äô : no grain
‚Äòg=p‚Äô : paper grain
‚Äòh=t‚Äô : high resolution mode, 5940‚Ää√ó‚Ää8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append ‚Äú&g=p&h=t‚Äù to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Plottable Era: (II) Medieval #184
metadata.description:
'Plottable Era: (II) Medieval' is the second generator in the "Era" generators series, highlighting different periods and civilizations. Following "Primitive", this new series shows epic battle in a medieval scenery with mountains, castles, and ships.

Each NFT is a recipe to a physical plot (A4) and utilizes the Redeemables feature of fxhash, allowing owners to unlock a physical plot directly coming from @greweb's pen plotter.

The NFT serves as the key to obtaining a physically plottable art piece. It exports an SVG file that can be used for plotting with pens. Plotter artists have the freedom to utilize their own materials and ship the completed artwork to collectors, provided they possess the NFT at the time of the request. To obtain the .SVG file, simply drag and drop it into a folder or right-click and save.

For those interested in the technical details, this work was created using WebGL + Rust + WASM and is licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0. Additional information and the source code for this piece can be found at this link: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-era-medieval

metadata.name: GRAPHEME #251
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke. 
www.tribute-hwf.com

‚ÄúOne criterion for art involves the process used by the artist for shaping the work. In the special case of mathematically supported fine art, the artmaking process occurs in a mathematically defined operation that allows the generation and transformation of images, methods used for picture processing.‚Äù - Herbert W. Franke

I first came across Franke‚Äôs ‚ÄòOrnamental Alphabets‚Äô in his book ùòäùò∞ùòÆùò±ùò∂ùòµùò¶ùò≥ ùòéùò≥ùò¢ùò±ùò©ùò™ùò§ùò¥ - ùòäùò∞ùòÆùò±ùò∂ùòµùò¶ùò≥ ùòàùò≥ùòµ, and was intrigued with the idea of using a simple letterform to explore different generative image processing techniques. 

I‚Äôve used letters and writing in my work for a long time, both with letterpress printing and in my asemic poetry programs. With asemic writing, I generate unrecognizable letters to reference text, and here I use recognizable letterforms removed from their typical function as language signifiers. 

My goal with this project was to build as much texture and layering as possible by warping and collaging the letters together in various ways. The font I‚Äôm using is a design I made years ago to supplement my wood type collection for printing. I really enjoyed being able to bring that part of my past work into my generative art practice. 

Each image is composed of the letters found in the hash for that piece, divided into either vowels or consonants. The program builds on a technique I‚Äôve used before, where I generate an image to an off-screen canvas and then dive through the pixels to pull out the color and form I want to surface in the final image.

25% of the primary sales will be donated on-chain to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke. These funds will be used by ZKM Karlsruhe to digitize Franke‚Äôs 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. Any additional funds raised will be donated to the R√ºtgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.

- Press ‚ÄúR‚Äù to increase the pixel density and reload the image (this can be render intensive and will create a really large file suitable for printing)
- Press ‚ÄúS‚Äù to save a copy

Made with p5js
Artist: Sarah Ridgley
October, 2022

metadata.name: Jajim #65
metadata.description:
The main idea of the "Jajim" is to divide a square into smaller parts in such a way that each variation has its original and unique composition. The role of lines is such that sometimes they help the dynamics of the composition and sometimes they appear in the form of texture and its contrast with empty spaces leads to the visual richness of the work. I avoided drawing various visual elements in favor of clarity of composition. Also, in order to avoid exaggeration, I used colors sparingly because I think they will have a stronger impact in their occasional presence.

Created using p5.js.

metadata.name: Dialog Box #241
metadata.description:
Dialog Box is a playful generative art project that invites viewers to engage with the concept of choice in the digital age. Inspired by the early Mac OS, the artwork presents an interface of two buttons, each symbolizing a choice steeped in 80s and 90s pop culture, from the serious to the lighthearted.

https://medium.com/@duaneking/dialog-box-by-duane-king-scott-brewer-and-adam-moliski-abab7afd3519
